import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>Jephthah's description as 'a mighty warrior, the son of a prostitute' (<em>gibbor ḥayil ben-ʾiššāh zônāh</em>) places him in a well-defined social category in the ancient Near East: the son of a secondary or irregular union who had some claim to the father's name but was legally disadvantaged regarding inheritance. The Code of Hammurabi (§170–171) specifies that a concubine's children could be acknowledged by their father and receive inheritance rights, but only if the father formally declared 'my children' — if not, only the wife's children inherited, though the concubine's sons received freedom. The situation in Judges 11 reflects the same social structure: Gilead had sons by his wife who expelled Jephthah on the grounds that he was not entitled to a share of the inheritance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The expulsion by the legitimate sons — 'you will not inherit in our father's house because you are the son of another woman' (<em>ʾiššāh ʾaḥeret</em>) — follows the logic of Mesopotamian inheritance law. The Middle Assyrian Laws (§A41) and Old Babylonian texts show that disputes over inheritance between sons of different status mothers were common and legally contentious. The designation 'another woman' avoids the more explicit term for prostitute, focusing on the legal rather than moral argument: her children are 'other,' not the primary heirs. Jephthah's displacement from Gilead represents the systemic vulnerability of non-primary-status children in patrilineal societies.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jephthah fled to Tob — a region in northern Transjordan, east of the Jordan, probably the area of modern et-Taiyibeh. He gathered 'empty/worthless men' (<em>ʾănāšîm rêqîm</em>) around him — the same term used of Abimelech's hired men (9:4) and of the social outcasts who gathered around David at Adullam (1 Sam 22:2: 'everyone who was in distress, in debt, or discontented'). The pattern of a displaced, landless military entrepreneur gathering a warband of social margins is well-attested in the ancient Near East: the Habiru/Apiru texts from Amarna (14th century BCE) describe similar groups of stateless warriors available for hire to city-states in crisis. Jephthah as a Habiru-type figure gives historical texture to his social situation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Ammonite war — 'the sons of Ammon made war against Israel' — is the covenant crisis that transforms Jephthah from outcast to needed leader. Ammon's territory was east of Gilead across the Jabbok River, in the region of modern Jordan. The Ammonite state emerged as a recognizable polity in Iron Age I, approximately contemporary with Israel's consolidation. The Amarna letters and later Assyrian records document Ammon as a small but persistent trans-Jordanian kingdom. The territorial dispute behind the war (vv12-28 will make this explicit) reflects the contested borderlands between Israelite-claimed Gilead and Ammonite-claimed highlands east of the Jabbok.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The elders of Gilead going to fetch Jephthah from Tob is a remarkable social reversal — the expelled son is sought by the very community that expelled him. The word <em>zāqēn</em> (elder, H2205) indicates the tribal leadership council that functioned as the governing body of non-monarchic Israelite communities. In the pre-monarchic period, the elders were the primary judicial and executive authority (cf. Ruth 4:1-12, where elders sit at the gate for a legal transaction). Their approach to Jephthah enacts the shame of the community's own prior injustice — they need what they discarded.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The request 'come be our commander' uses <em>qāṣîn</em> (H7101, commander/ruler/judge — one who decides and leads) — a military-judicial title broader than the usual military terms. In ANE city-states, the <em>rabiānum</em> (chief man) or <em>šapiṭum</em> (judge) combined judicial and military functions during crises. The elders' offer reflects the Iron Age Israelite understanding that a military crisis required someone with both the authority to lead battle and the standing to adjudicate disputes — functions the later monarchy would institutionalize but that here remain in the hands of a chosen military leader.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jephthah's counter-accusation — 'did you not hate me and drive me from my father's house? Why have you come to me now when you are in trouble?' — is a formal legal challenge in covenant language. <em>śānēʾ</em> (H8130, to hate) in ANE legal contexts often refers not to emotional hatred but to the formal rejection of a covenant relationship — divorce documents and inheritance documents use 'hate' to describe the legal act of repudiation. Jephthah is accusing the elders of having formally repudiated him; their current need does not erase that repudiation without formal acknowledgment.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The elders' revised offer — 'we have turned back to you now' with the promise to make him 'head' (<em>rōʾš</em>, H7218) over all Gilead — escalates the original request. The distinction between <em>qāṣîn</em> (commander, v6) and <em>rōʾš</em> (head/chief) is significant: head implies not just military leadership but permanent political authority over the community. The elders are offering Jephthah the very inheritance the family denied him — headship over the whole clan — in exchange for military service. This transforms the negotiation from desperation-hire to covenant restoration.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jephthah's conditional — 'if you bring me back to fight the Ammonites and YHWH gives them to me, I will be your head' — introduces YHWH as the decisive party. The condition is not merely military success but specifically YHWH's gift of victory (<em>nātan YHWH ləpānay</em>, YHWH gives them before me). This reflects the holy war theology of the period: military victory is YHWH's to give, not something a commander achieves independently. Jephthah is stating that the outcome depends on divine action, not on his own military prowess — a theological positioning that will make his subsequent vow more intelligible.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The elders' oath — 'YHWH will be witness between us, if we do not do according to your word' — invokes YHWH as the guarantor of covenant agreement. The formula <em>YHWH yihyeh šōmēaʿ bênênû</em> (YHWH will be hearing/witnessing between us) is a covenant oath formula in which the deity serves as both witness and enforcer of the agreement. ANE suzerain treaties regularly invoke the divine pantheon as witnesses; the Israelite formula narrows this to YHWH alone. Covenant oaths between parties were legally binding in the ancient world — oath-breaking could bring divine punishment, making such formulas far more than polite agreements.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jephthah 'stated all his words before YHWH at Mizpah' — the covenant agreement is ratified at a sanctuary. Mizpah of Gilead (a different location from the Benjamin Mizpah of 20:1) was an important Transjordanian cultic site; 'before YHWH' indicates a sanctuary where YHWH's presence was recognized. The public covenant ratification at a cultic site transforms the agreement from a private contract into a solemn covenant before the divine witness just invoked. This follows ANE treaty protocol precisely: the treaty text was deposited in the sanctuary of the divine witness (cf. the two stone tablets deposited in the ark).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jephthah's diplomatic negotiation with Ammon (vv12-28) is the longest diplomatic exchange in Judges and one of the most detailed examples of ancient Near Eastern diplomatic argument in the Bible. The exchange follows the standard ANE diplomatic messenger form: sender, message recipient, and the formal 'thus says X' structure. Jephthah's opening question — 'what is between you and me that you have come to fight against me in my land?' — uses the standard covenant dispute formula (<em>mah-lî wālāk</em>, what is to me and to you?) that appears from Abraham (Gen 23) through the NT (John 2:4).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Ammonite king's claim — 'Israel took away my land from the Arnon to the Jabbok and to the Jordan when they came out of Egypt; now restore these lands peaceably' — is a territorial claim based on the Israelite conquest narrative. The Arnon River forms the southern border of the Moabite plateau; the Jabbok is further north. The region between them (modern central Jordan) was disputed between Moab, Ammon, and Israel during Iron Age I. The Ammonite claim that this territory was historically theirs is the historical basis for the entire negotiation, and Jephthah's counter-argument will systematically refute it using the same historical evidence.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jephthah sends messengers back — the formal counter-response in the ANE diplomatic exchange. The multi-messenger structure (each round of negotiation involving messengers traveling between the two parties) reflects the standard practice of ancient diplomacy: no direct confrontation between leaders, all communication through formal envoys who must transmit the exact words of their sender. The repetition of the formal structure in this exchange (vv12, 14) signals to the audience that a full diplomatic process is being followed — Jephthah is not merely a rough warrior but a capable diplomatist who follows proper protocol.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jephthah's counter-claim — 'Israel did not take away the land of Moab or the land of the Ammonites' — opens with a precise historical correction. The land in question was not Moabite or Ammonite but was taken from Sihon king of the Amorites (vv19-22), who had himself previously taken it from Moab (v22 — 'for Arnon is the border of Moab'). This is a sophisticated argument: Israel's right of conquest was against the Amorites, not against Moab or Ammon, so Moabite and Ammonite claims are irrelevant to the current dispute. Jephthah is applying the principle of uti possidetis — the right of conquest over what was actually taken by force.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The rehearsal of the wilderness journey — Israel traveling from Egypt to Kadesh through the wilderness, sending messengers to Edom and Moab who refused passage — draws on the Numbers narrative (Num 20-21). The detailed recitation of the historical itinerary is a diplomatic convention: in ANE treaty and boundary disputes, the historical narrative of how each party came to possess its territory was the primary legal argument. Hittite treaties include historical preambles precisely because possession history was the strongest legal title. Jephthah is deploying historical narrative as legal argument.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The refusal of Edom and Moab to grant passage — 'Israel sent messengers to the king of Edom... and also to the king of Moab, but he was not willing' — is cited from the wilderness wandering tradition (Num 20:14-21 for Edom; there is no explicit parallel for Moab in Numbers, though Num 22:1 shows Moab's hostility). Jephthah's version may reflect a broader tradition not fully preserved in the Pentateuch. The detail serves his argument: Israel respected the territorial rights of Edom and Moab by seeking permission rather than forcing passage — a demonstration of Israel's non-aggressive stance toward neighboring peoples' legitimate territories.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Israel's travel around Edom and Moab — 'going through the wilderness and going around the land of Edom and Moab' — demonstrates Israel's respect for recognized territorial limits. The wilderness route taken to avoid these kingdoms confirms that Israel recognized their boundaries. This is Jephthah's strongest diplomatic point: if Israel was a land-grabber, it would have taken Edom and Moab too. The fact that it did not, and in fact went out of its way to avoid their territory, establishes that Israel's claims are not expansionist but specifically rooted in the particular history of the Amorite conquest.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Sihon narrative — Israel sending messengers to Sihon king of the Amorites at Heshbon requesting passage, Sihon refusing, Israel defeating Sihon in battle — is drawn directly from Num 21:21-25. Heshbon (modern Tell Hesban, south of Amman) was the Amorite capital in Transjordan. Archaeological excavations at Tell Hesban show Iron Age I occupation, though the LBA stratigraphy is complex. The Amorites (as distinct from Ammonites and Moabites) were the legitimate target of Israel's conquest — Sihon's aggressive refusal of passage provoked the war that gave Israel the territory.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Sihon's refusal to trust Israel to pass through — 'Sihon did not trust Israel to pass through his territory, but assembled all his people and camped at Jahaz' — sets up the legal point: Israel did not ambush or invade but was attacked. <em>bāṭaḥ</em> (H982, to trust/rely on — Sihon 'did not trust') — the term implies a conscious decision not to grant safe passage even though Israel's request was legitimate. The assembled army and battle camp at Jahaz (possibly modern Khirbet el-Medeiyineh) turned a request for passage into a military confrontation that Israel won. The defeat of the aggressor legitimized Israel's possession.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The formula 'YHWH the God of Israel gave Sihon and all his people into Israel's hand' invokes the holy war theology: the land was YHWH's to give, and YHWH gave it. This is not simply the winner's claim — it is a theological interpretation of the military outcome that frames the possession as divinely authorized. The divine gift framework is precisely what Jephthah will use in v24 to challenge the Ammonite position: just as Chemosh gives land to Ammon (Jephthah grants this for the sake of argument), YHWH has given this land to Israel.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The territorial scope — 'all the border of the Amorites, from Arnon to the Jabbok and from the wilderness to the Jordan' — exactly defines the disputed region using the river boundaries that the Ammonites claim. Jephthah's argument closes the loop: the territory the Ammonites claim is precisely the Amorite territory that Israel legitimately took from Sihon. The geographic precision (Arnon = south boundary, Jabbok = north boundary, wilderness = east, Jordan = west) maps onto the boundary description of the Ammonite territorial claim in v13. Jephthah has matched the Ammonite claim point by point.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The theological climax of Jephthah's argument — 'YHWH the God of Israel dispossessed the Amorites before his people Israel; and shall you possess them?' — is the formal legal argument from divine title. In ANE territorial theology, each nation's god was the true owner of the land, with the human king as the god's vice-regent. Jephthah invokes this framework: YHWH, as the God of Israel, exercised his divine ownership by dispossessing the Amorites. Ammon cannot reclaim what YHWH transferred — the divine title is non-negotiable.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Is it not the case that what Chemosh your god gives you to possess, you possess?' — Jephthah's concessive argument grants the Ammonite premise (Chemosh gives them their territory) to make the parallel point: YHWH gives Israel its territory. This is often read as Jephthah acknowledging Chemosh's divinity, but it is better understood as a diplomatic concession — speaking the other party's theological language to make the parallel claim. ANE diplomatic texts regularly acknowledge the gods of treaty partners without implying belief in them. The mention of Chemosh rather than Milcom (Ammon's god) is a textual issue — Chemosh was Moab's god; possibly Jephthah is conflating the kingdoms, or the text has been influenced by a Moabite parallel tradition.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The appeal to Balak son of Zippor (king of Moab during the Numbers narrative) — 'did he ever contend against Israel or did he ever go to war with them?' — is a negative precedent argument. Balak's failure to press his territorial claim against Israel, despite having the opportunity, establishes that even the Moabite king recognized Israel's legitimate possession. This is ancient case law: if the prior claimant did not press a claim when he could, subsequent claimants have weakened standing. Jephthah is arguing that 300 years of non-contestation (v26) creates an adverse possession claim.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The '300 years' of Israelite possession argument is the strongest practical element of Jephthah's case: 'Israel dwelt in Heshbon and its villages, and in Aroer and its villages, and in all the cities that are on the banks of the Arnon for three hundred years. Why did you not recover them within that time?' This is the principle of acquisitive prescription in ancient Near Eastern law — extended, undisturbed possession creates legal title. The Ammonites had 300 years to press their claim; their current action is too late. The 300-year figure has chronological significance for dating the judges period, though its precision is debated.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Jephthah's closing formula — 'I have not sinned against you, but you do me wrong by making war against me. May YHWH the judge decide today between the sons of Israel and the sons of Ammon' — invokes the divine tribunal as the final arbiter of the dispute. <em>šōpēṭ</em> (H8199, judge) applied to YHWH is the highest court appeal available: when human diplomacy fails, the divine judge decides through the ordeal of battle. The formula 'may YHWH decide between us' appears in Gen 16:5 (Sarai to Abraham), Gen 31:53 (Jacob and Laban), and 1 Sam 24:12 (David to Saul) — it is a formal judicial appeal, not merely a pious wish.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The Ammonite king 'did not listen to the words of Jephthah' — the diplomatic process has failed. The rejection of the formal diplomatic argument legitimizes the war that follows: Jephthah has exhausted peaceful means. The refusal to hear a formal diplomatic appeal was recognized in ANE practice as the other party's acceptance of war — the Hittite treaties and Assyrian annals regularly note that an enemy 'did not hear' or 'did not submit' as the formal justification for military action. Jephthah's war against Ammon is thus presented as both legally justified (the historical argument) and divinely necessary (YHWH as judge).</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Spirit of YHWH coming on Jephthah (<em>rûaḥ YHWH ʿal-yiptāḥ</em>) follows the now-familiar pattern of pneumatic empowerment for the judge's military mission. Unlike Gideon (the Spirit 'clothed' him) or Samson (the Spirit 'rushed upon' him), the Spirit 'came upon' Jephthah — the Qal of <em>hāyāh ʿal</em> (to be upon/over) suggests a more sustained, hovering presence. The geographic sweep of his mustering — passing through Gilead, Manasseh, to Mizpah of Gilead — shows that the Spirit-empowerment has military-organizational effects: the same one who gathered a warband in Tob is now mustering the full tribal levy.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Jephthah's vow — 'if you will give the Ammonites into my hand, then whatever comes out of the doors of my house to meet me when I return in peace from the Ammonites shall be YHWH's, and I will offer it up as a burnt offering' — is a pre-battle vow well-attested in ancient Near Eastern practice. Military vows before battle appear in Punic inscriptions, Hittite prayer texts, and Ugaritic literature. The common form is: 'if god X gives me victory, I will give X something valuable in return.' The ambiguity of 'whatever comes out' (<em>hayyôṣēʾ ʾăšer yeṣēʾ</em>) — which could mean an animal coming out of a pen attached to the house, or a person — is the narrative's central tension.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The interpretation of Jephthah's vow is debated by ancient and modern commentators. The standard ANE reading of 'whatever comes out of the door of my house' in a pastoral context would be a large animal — the first animal to emerge from the livestock pen adjoining the house. Some rabbinic commentators (Rashi, Kimhi) argue Jephthah expected an animal. Others argue the clause 'I will offer it as a burnt offering' (<em>wəhaʿălîtîhû ʿôlāh</em>) requires an animal sacrifice, and that the daughter's fate was perpetual virginity rather than literal sacrifice. The Levitical law (Lev 27:1-8) provided for redeeming persons vowed to God — Jephthah's failure to use this provision (if he knew of it) is itself a theological comment on his faithlessness.</p>",
    "32": "<p>YHWH's giving the Ammonites into Jephthah's hand is recorded without theological editorial — the victory is simply reported. The geographical extent of the battle (vv32-33) — twenty cities from Aroer to the region of Minnith and Abel-keramim — describes a comprehensive defeat of Ammonite territory in the southern part of their kingdom. This is the fulfillment of the holy war oracle: YHWH has decided between Israel and Ammon as the divine judge. The victory is granted; the question of the vow is now unavoidable.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The cities enumerated in Jephthah's victory — Aroer (on the Arnon), Minnith (possibly modern Khirbet Hamzeh north of Heshbon), and Abel-keramim ('meadow of vineyards,' unidentified) — trace a military advance northward through Ammonite territory toward the capital Rabbah (modern Amman). Twenty cities is a substantial conquest. The phrase 'a very great defeat' (<em>makkāh gədôlāh məʾōd</em>) is the stereotyped formula for decisive holy war victory (cf. Josh 10:10; 1 Sam 4:10). The Ammonites 'were subdued' (<em>wayyikāneʿû</em>) — the covenant verb of humiliation at the hands of YHWH's people.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Jephthah's return to Mizpah — and his daughter coming out first with tambourines and dances — fulfills the worst interpretation of the vow. The detail that she was 'his only child' (<em>yəḥîḏāh</em>, H3173 — only/unique/only one) is the narrative's most pointed word: the same word used of Isaac in Gen 22:2, the only son whom Abraham was asked to give. The daughter's coming out with tambourines to celebrate her father's victory mirrors Miriam's celebration after the Red Sea (Exod 15:20) and the women who celebrated Saul and David's victories (1 Sam 18:6-7). The celebratory exit tradition makes her first exit cruelly ironic.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Jephthah's response — 'Alas, my daughter! You have brought me very low and you have become the cause of great trouble to me; for I have opened my mouth to YHWH, and I cannot take it back' — invokes the ANE principle of the inviolability of a solemn vow. <em>pāṣîtî pî ʾel-YHWH</em> (I have opened my mouth to YHWH) is the most binding form of oath — a word spoken to the deity cannot be retracted without incurring divine punishment. Num 30:2 states: 'If a man vows a vow to YHWH or swears an oath to bind himself by a pledge, he shall not break his word; he shall do according to all that proceeds out of his mouth.' Jephthah is applying this principle, though his failure to seek a priest's counsel about redeeming his daughter (Lev 27) shows his theological ignorance.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The daughter's response — 'My father, you have opened your mouth to YHWH; do to me according to what has gone out of your mouth, now that YHWH has avenged you on your enemies, on the Ammonites' — is one of the most remarkable displays of piety in Judges. She prioritizes the covenant obligation her father has incurred over her own life or (on the 'perpetual virginity' reading) her marriage prospects. The acceptance of a divine will that brings personal loss echoes Isaac's passive compliance at Moriah — in both cases, the one offered does not resist.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The daughter's request — two months to 'roam on the mountains and weep for my virginity with my companions' — reflects a specific cultural practice. In many ANE societies, a young woman's virginity was her most socially valued asset — it was the precondition for marriage, which was the only socially recognized path to status, children, and security. The loss of the marriage future was therefore the deepest possible personal loss for an unmarried woman. The 'weeping for virginity' is not primarily about sexual status but about the loss of the life-path that made a woman's social existence possible.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The 'custom in Israel' described in vv39-40 — that Israelite women went out four days a year to commemorate Jephthah's daughter — is unique in the Hebrew Bible. The annual female mourning ritual has parallels in ANE female mourning for Tammuz (the dying-and-rising vegetation deity of Mesopotamia), a practice Ezekiel condemns at the temple gate (Ezek 8:14). Some scholars see the Jephthah daughter narrative as an Israelite aetiological story explaining a pre-existing female mourning festival. Whether this is correct, the institution of the ritual marks the daughter as a figure of public grief — her unnamed death is commemorated by name, annually, by women.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Jephthah fulfilled his vow — the text's terse statement leaves the nature of the fulfillment ambiguous, though the narrative structure points toward literal sacrifice. The phrase 'she did not know a man' (<em>wəhîʾ lōʾ-yāḏəʿāh ʾîš</em>) is either a narrative note confirming her virginity before death (if literally sacrificed) or the substance of her dedication (if devoted to perpetual religious virginity). The Targum and many Rabbinic interpreters chose the latter to avoid the implication of human sacrifice. The Septuagint's translation is neutral. The narrative leaves the reader in the same position as Jephthah: reckoning with the cost of vows made without wisdom.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The annual four-day commemoration by women of Israel — 'to rehearse (<em>lətannôt</em>, to recount/celebrate)' Jephthah's daughter — is the only female-centered religious observance established in the book of Judges. The verb <em>tānāh</em> (H8567, to celebrate/recount — the same root as 'rehearse' in 5:11, where the righteous acts of YHWH are rehearsed at the watering places) indicates a ritual of communal remembrance, not mere mourning. Her un-named status through the narrative — she is only 'his daughter' — contrasts with the practice of annual memorial that preserves her memory without her name. The community of women who go out to the mountains for four days creates a liminal female space that honors what institutional religion had no category for.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The Ephraimite confrontation — 'the men of Ephraim were called to arms... and said to Jephthah: why did you cross over to fight against the Ammonites and did not call us to go with you?' — is a repeat of the conflict with Gideon (8:1-3). Ephraim's tribal self-assertion against successful military leaders reflects the demographic and political weight of the Ephraimite highlands: Ephraim was the dominant tribe of the central hill country, with significant population and traditional prestige (the sanctuary at Shiloh was in Ephraim; Joshua was an Ephraimite). The threat to 'burn your house over you' is extreme — escalating from the verbal challenge of the Gideon incident to a threat of lethal retribution.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jephthah's response — 'I and my people were in great dispute with the Ammonites, and when I called you, you did not save me from their hand' — differs from Gideon's diplomatic deflection (8:2-3). Where Gideon flattered Ephraim, Jephthah directly challenges their complaint with a counter-factual: I did call you, and you did not come. This may reflect actual events not narrated in ch11, or Jephthah may be using the call to mustering (11:29) as covering all tribes. The contrast in approach — Gideon the diplomat, Jephthah the combatant — produces opposite outcomes: Gideon averted war, Jephthah triggers it.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jephthah's self-description — 'I took my life in my hand and crossed over against the Ammonites, and YHWH gave them into my hand' — is idiomatic for extreme personal risk. The phrase 'to put one's life in one's hand' (<em>śamtî napšî bəkappî</em>) appears in 1 Sam 19:5 (Jonathan speaking of David) and 1 Sam 28:21 (the witch of Endor) and means accepting mortal danger. The addition 'why then have you come up against me today to fight against me?' reframes the Ephraimite complaint as unprovoked aggression against a man who risked his life for Israel. Jephthah's argument is that the Ephraimites are attacking the very person who just saved the region they did not help defend.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jephthah gathered the men of Gilead and fought Ephraim — the tribal war that follows is a civil conflict with long-term consequences. The Ephraimite insult ('you Gileadites are fugitives of Ephraim, in the midst of Ephraim and Manasseh') reveals the Transjordanian tribes' ambiguous status within the Israelite confederation. The charge of being 'fugitives' (<em>pəlîṭê</em>, escapees/refugees) may reflect an actual historical memory: Transjordanian tribes were seen by western Israelites as a secondary, displaced group rather than full members of the covenant community. This perceived status inferiority is the social dynamic behind the Ephraimite contempt.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Gileadites' capture of the Jordan fords is classic Iron Age military tactics: control of the river crossings meant control of retreat routes. The Jordan River between Gilead and the western tribes had few fordable points in the Iron Age — the seasonal flooding and steep banks made crossing dangerous except at specific shallow points. The Gileadite seizure of 'the fords of the Jordan before Ephraim' cut off the retreating Ephraimite survivors from their homeland — a classic envelopment tactic that transformed a retreat into a rout.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Shibboleth test — 'say now Shibboleth, and he said Sibboleth' — is the most famous example of dialect difference as social identifier in the ancient world. <em>Šibbōlet</em> (H7641) means either 'flowing stream/flood' or 'ear of grain'; the specific word choice was probably designed to expose a phonological distinction. The Ephraimite dialect apparently could not produce the initial /š/ (shin) sound and substituted /s/ (samek). Dialect differences in Canaanite/Hebrew regional variants are attested in comparative Semitic linguistics: the Amarna tablets show scribal differences between Canaanite dialects, and linguistic geography suggests that the Jordan River was a phonological boundary. The test is linguistically sophisticated: it isolates a single phoneme that betrayed tribal origin regardless of the speaker's attempts to disguise it.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jephthah judged Israel six years and was buried in the cities of Gilead — the Transjordanian location of his burial (rather than a single city) has puzzled commentators. The phrase 'cities of Gilead' may reflect a textual difficulty (perhaps 'in his city of Gilead' or 'Mizpah of Gilead') or may indicate that his authority was diffuse, distributed across the regional cluster. His six-year tenure is the shortest of the major judges, bracketed by the personal tragedy of his daughter and the fratricidal war with Ephraim. The formulaic judge notice in v7 treats his tenure as officially complete, but the narrative has been anything but straightforward.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The minor judge notices for Ibzan, Elon, and Abdon (vv8-15) follow a formulaic structure: name, home territory, length of rule, details about sons/daughters/donkeys indicating wealth and status, and burial notice. These brief notices preserve historical memory of leadership figures whose stories were not elaborated. Ibzan of Bethlehem (v8-10) — possibly the Bethlehem of Zebulun (Josh 19:15) rather than Judah, given the regional context — had thirty sons and thirty daughters, with extensive marriage alliances in both directions. The large family with strategic intermarriage reflects the practice of using marriage as political alliance-building in the Iron Age Levant.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ibzan's thirty sons and thirty daughters 'sent abroad' and 'brought in from abroad' for marriage reflects a system of cross-tribal and possibly cross-ethnic marriage alliances that maintained political stability in the pre-monarchic period. Marriage was the primary tool of diplomacy in the ancient Near East (as extensively documented in the Amarna letters, where Egyptian pharaohs exchanged daughters with Mitanni, Babylonian, and Canaanite kings). A leader who could arrange sixty marriages was one with enormous social network and resources — the size of the marriage portfolio signals political power in non-monetary terms.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ibzan judged Israel seven years — the formula 'judged Israel X years' is the Deuteronomistic framework applied consistently to both major and minor judges. The seven-year tenure is not elaborated; Ibzan joins the list of leaders whose tenure is preserved without narrative development. His burial at Bethlehem closes the notice in the same formulaic way as the major judge notices, suggesting that the compiler of Judges had brief records for these figures and preserved them faithfully without elaboration.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Elon the Zebulonite judged Israel ten years. The notice is the most minimal in Judges — name, tribe, duration, death, and burial at Aijalon in Zebulun. No family details, no military action, no theological evaluation. The Zebulunite tribal region (the lower Galilee, between the Jezreel Valley and the northern coast) was the area that had been praised in the Song of Deborah (5:18) for its military courage. Elon's decade of leadership in this region falls between the Jephthah-Samson period, occupying a chronological space the narrative does not fill with conflict — possibly a period of relative stability in the northern territories.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Elon's burial at Aijalon in Zebulun (a different Aijalon from the Danite Aijalon of Josh 19:42 and 1 Sam 14:31) closes this minimal notice. The geographic precision of burial locations in the judge formulas served as a memorialization function — the grave of a judge was a community landmark, a site of memory. In the ancient Near East, the tombs of ancestors and leaders were venerated as places of ongoing ancestral presence; knowing where a judge was buried preserved a tangible connection to the era of his leadership. These burial notices are thus not mere obituary formulas but geographic-theological markers.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Abdon son of Hillel the Pirathonite judged Israel eight years — the Pirathonites were from Pirathon in Ephraim (1 Chr 27:14 identifies a later Pirathonite as the commander of the monthly levy for the fifth month, suggesting a prominent clan). Abdon represents Ephraimite leadership after the catastrophic tribal war of 12:1-6 — the same tribal region that had just been humiliated by Gilead now provides a judge. This may reflect the compiler's interest in showing the continuity of the tribal system despite intra-tribal violence.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Abdon's family — 'he had forty sons and thirty grandsons who rode on seventy donkeys' — is the most elaborated of the minor judge family notices. The donkey-riding sons and grandsons echo the description of Jair's sons who rode on thirty donkeys in 10:4, and anticipate the sons of the minor judges as symbols of wealth and status. In the Iron Age Levant, a donkey was a significant possession — estimates suggest that a working donkey represented approximately one month's agricultural wage. Seventy donkeys among the extended family signals considerable wealth accumulated across two generations of Abdon's house.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Abdon's burial 'at Pirathon in the land of Ephraim, in the hill country of the Amalekites' — the geographic designation 'hill country of the Amalekites' (<em>har haʿămālēqî</em>) is puzzling: Amalekites were normally associated with the Negev and Sinai desert, not the Ephraimite highlands. This either reflects a local tradition of Amalekite presence in the hill country (cf. 5:14, which mentions 'Amalek' in what appears to be Ephraimite territory), or a corruption in the text. With Abdon's death the minor judge sequence closes, and the narrative shifts to the longest and most complex single judge narrative in the book — Samson.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The Philistine oppression of forty years — the longest in Judges — frames the Samson narrative (chs13-16). The Philistines were one of the Sea Peoples who settled the Levantine coast around 1200 BCE following the collapse of the LBA palace economies. They established a pentapolis of five city-states: Gaza, Ashkelon, Ashdod, Ekron (Tel Miqne), and Gath — well-attested archaeologically by their distinctive Mycenaean-derived pottery (the Philistine bichrome ware), hearth-houses, and Aegean-style religious iconography. By Iron Age I the Philistines had become the dominant military power of the coastal plain, with iron technology giving them a significant military advantage (cf. 1 Sam 13:19-22: Israel had no iron tools; the Philistines controlled iron-working). The forty-year oppression reflects the full establishment of Philistine hegemony before Samson's one-man disruption of it.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Manoah of Zorah from the tribe of Dan — the geographic context is significant. Zorah (modern Sar'ah) and Eshtaol were Dan's territory in the foothills (Shephelah) between the coastal plain and the Judean highlands, directly on the border of Philistine territory. This was a contested zone: Dan's original allotment (Josh 19:40-48) had been largely unsuccessful because of Amorite and Philistine pressure (Judg 1:34 — 'the Amorites pressed the Danites back into the hill country'), which led to Dan's northern migration (ch18). The remaining Danites in the Zorah-Eshtaol area were living in the most dangerous frontier zone in Israel — the buffer between Philistia and the highlands. Manoah's barren wife will bear the man who will 'begin to save Israel from the hand of the Philistines' (v5).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The angel of YHWH's appearance to the unnamed wife of Manoah follows the pattern of divine birth announcements in Genesis: Sarah (Gen 18:10-14), Rebekah (Gen 25:23), and Rachel (Gen 30:22) all receive divine intervention in the context of barrenness. In the ancient Near East, barrenness was understood as a divine withholding of fertility — the womb was 'closed' by divine decision and could be 'opened' only by divine action (Gen 29:31; 30:22). The divine birth announcement to a barren woman is thus an act of sovereign creation: YHWH is not ratifying a natural pregnancy but initiating one that would not otherwise occur. The pattern is: barrenness → divine appearance → pregnancy → special child → deliverer. Samson is the last in this series before the most significant — John the Baptist and Jesus — in Luke 1.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The prenatal Nazirite instructions — 'now therefore be careful to drink no wine or strong drink, and eat nothing unclean' — extend the Nazirite restrictions to the mother during pregnancy. The Nazirite vow (Num 6:1-21) normally applied to an individual who voluntarily undertook it for a specific period; it involved abstention from wine and fermented drink, from shaving the head, and from contact with the dead. The prenatal application — which Num 6 does not mention — is unique to Samson and creates a Nazirite dedicated from conception. The mother's dietary restrictions reflect the ancient understanding that what the mother consumed affected the developing child — an intuition of prenatal influence that modern nutritional science has confirmed in principle.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'For behold, you are with child and shall bear a son. No razor shall come on his head, for the child shall be a Nazirite to God from the womb, and he shall begin to save Israel from the hand of the Philistines.' The permanent Nazirite vow ('from the womb') is unique — even John the Baptist's prenatal dedication (Luke 1:15) uses similar language ('he will be filled with the Holy Spirit, even from his mother's womb'). The long hair of the Nazirite was the external sign of the vow's duration; cutting it would end the vow. That Samson's hair cannot be cut means the vow is unconditional and permanent — or rather, that Samson himself is the condition: when he violates the vow, the vow terminates. The phrase 'begin to save' (<em>lāhāhel</em> lĕhôšîaʿ) is unusual — YHWH will save Israel through Samson, but only begin to do so; the full deliverance will require David and the early monarchy.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The wife's report to her husband describes the angelic visitor as 'a man of God' (<em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) whose appearance was 'very awesome' or 'like the appearance of the angel of God' — she did not initially know he was the angel of YHWH. The term <em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em> (man of God) is normally used of prophets (Moses in Deut 33:1, Elijah in 1 Kgs 17:18, Elisha in 2 Kgs 4:7) — it designates a human figure who speaks with divine authority. Her description of his appearance as 'very awesome' (<em>nôrāʾ məʾōd</em>, H3372) suggests she perceived something numinous about him even if she could not identify him precisely.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The woman reports the angel's specific instructions — 'behold, you shall conceive and bear a son; now drink no wine or strong drink and eat nothing unclean, for the child shall be a Nazirite to God from the womb to the day of his death' — with the significant addition 'to the day of his death.' The permanent, lifelong Nazirite dedication 'until the day of his death' makes explicit what was implied in v5: there is no planned end to this vow. Ordinary Nazirites completed their vow and returned to normal life (Num 6:13-21). Samson's vow is permanent — his long hair is his entire identity as YHWH's instrument.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Manoah's prayer — 'O Lord, please let the man of God you sent come again to us and teach us what we shall do with the child who will be born' — is a request for divine instruction about child-rearing in the context of a divine commissioning. In the ancient Near East, divine birth announcements to kings (Egyptian royal birth scenes show the god forming the royal child, with instructions about the child's destiny) typically included guidance for the child's upbringing. Manoah's request follows this pattern: the divine commission includes not just the announcement but the instruction manual. The request is pious, though the angel's ultimate response (v12) will be to reiterate what he already said — the instructions have already been given.</p>",
    "9": "<p>God 'listened to the voice of Manoah' — the phrase <em>wayyišmaʿ ʾĕlōhîm bəqôl mānôaḥ</em> (God heard in the voice of Manoah) reflects the standard Hebrew idiom for answered prayer. The angel returns — but comes again to the wife alone, while she is sitting in the field and Manoah is not with her. This detail (repeated in v11: 'Manoah got up and followed his wife') consistently places the woman as the primary recipient of the divine communication, with Manoah as the secondary figure who has to be brought to the encounter. The gendered dynamics of the theophany are deliberate: YHWH chose to reveal himself to the woman, who then brings her husband into the encounter.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The woman ran quickly to tell her husband — her responsiveness to the divine messenger contrasts with Manoah's absence. The quick running to fetch Manoah mirrors Sarah's quick preparation (Gen 18:6) in the theophany at Mamre. In the social structure of the ancient household, the wife's role as the first to receive and transmit the divine communication inverts expected hierarchies — the husband is the head of household, but YHWH approaches through the wife. This pattern of divine communication through non-primary household members (younger sons, barren wives, women) is one of Judges' consistent theological notes.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Manoah's question to the returning angel — 'Are you the man who spoke to this woman?' — establishes continuity with the first appearance and begins the formal confirmation dialogue. The angel's 'I am' (<em>ʾănî</em>, simple first-person self-identification) is the minimal affirmation. Manoah's subsequent question (v12) — 'when your words come true, what is to be the boy's way of life, and what is his mission?' — asks for clarification of upbringing instructions. The distinction between 'way of life' (<em>mišpāṭ hannaʿar</em>, the custom/manner of the young man) and 'mission' (<em>maʿăśēhû</em>, his work/deed) reflects the ANE interest in both the rearing conditions and the purpose of a specially destined child.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Manoah's request for instruction 'when your words come true' is interesting: he is asking about the post-birth period, assuming the announcement will be fulfilled. The conditional grammar is not doubt but planning — 'when this happens, how do we raise him?' The angel's response (vv13-14) repeats what was already said to the woman: all the Nazirite restrictions apply. The repetition serves a confirmatory function — the husband receives the same instruction as the wife, creating double attestation. In ANE law, important transactions required witnesses and confirmation; the angel's repetition constitutes the second witnessing of the divine commission.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The angel's instruction to Manoah — 'of all that I said to the woman let her be careful' — places the mother as the primary responsible party for the prenatal restrictions. In the ancient household, the pregnant woman's dietary and behavioral restrictions were well-understood through practical medicine: ANE medical texts (the Diagnostic Handbook from Nineveh, Akkadian birth omens) document restrictions on pregnant women's food and activity. The instruction to the father that the mother must be careful is consistent with an ANE understanding of the mother as the agent responsible for the child's prenatal environment, with the father as the authority who must ensure her compliance.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The comprehensive Nazirite restrictions are restated: no grapevine products (from seeds to skins, not just wine), no fermented drink, no unclean food — but notably no explicit mention of the razor or the dead. The wine prohibition is the most elaborated aspect of the prenatal restriction, possibly because the consumption of wine in pregnancy was a common practice that needed the strongest prohibition. The expansion 'all that comes from the vine' (<em>kol ʾăšer yeṣēʾ miggepen hayyayin</em>) covers even grape seeds and skins — a more comprehensive prohibition than Num 6:4. This suggests that the Nazirite vow was being interpreted in its strictest sense for this uniquely permanent dedication.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Manoah's offer to prepare a young goat for the angel — 'let us detain you and prepare a young goat for you' — follows the standard hospitality protocol for divine or angelic visitors. The same offer is made to the three visitors at Mamre (Gen 18:7), to the angel at Gideon's theophany (6:19), and implicitly to the strangers at Lot's house (Gen 19:2-3). The hospitality meal is the ritual of welcome and reciprocity that precedes formal interaction. The angel's redirection of the meal from consumption to offering (v16) again parallels the Gideon theophany: the food prepared for a guest becomes a sacrifice.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The angel's refusal to eat — 'I will not eat of your bread, but if you prepare a burnt offering, offer it to YHWH' — reveals his true identity while maintaining the fiction of uncertainty. The clause 'for Manoah did not know that he was the angel of YHWH' is the narrator's aside confirming what the audience suspects. The refusal to eat mortal food is a consistent feature of ANE angelology: divine beings do not consume human food in the way humans do (cf. Gen 18:8 — the visitors at Mamre appear to eat, but the theophany is confirmed when they have human appearance but divine knowledge). The angel's direction of worship to YHWH rather than to himself anticipates the NT angel who refuses worship (Rev 19:10; 22:9).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Manoah's question — 'what is your name?' — follows a pattern in theophany narratives: Jacob asks the name of his wrestling opponent (Gen 32:29, 'tell me your name' — refused), Moses asks YHWH's name (Exod 3:13-14 — given with 'I am who I am'). Manoah's purpose is explicitly honorific: 'so that when your words come true, we may honor you' (<em>wəkibbaḏnûkā</em>, we will honor/glorify you). The request is for the name as the basis for future thanksgiving and honor — a legitimate pious motive. The refusal of the name that follows turns this act of seeking into an act of instruction: the angel's identity is not available for human honorification.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The angel's answer — 'why do you ask my name, seeing it is wonderful (<em>pelîʾî</em>)?' — is one of the most theologically pregnant phrases in the Samson narrative. <em>Pelîʾ</em> (H6383, wonderful/incomprehensible/beyond understanding) is a cognate of <em>peleʾ</em> (H6382, wonder/marvel) used in Isa 9:6: 'and his name shall be called Wonderful (<em>peleʾ</em>).' Whether the angel is saying his name IS 'Wonderful' or that his name is 'too wonderful to tell' (i.e., incomprehensible) is debated. In context, both readings are coherent: the angel's identity is identified with the incomprehensible divine name. The connection to Isa 9:6 suggests that later readers heard this as a pre-incarnate self-identification of the Son whose name is Wonderful.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Manoah's offering of a young goat and grain offering (<em>minḥāh</em>) on the rock — 'doing wonders' (<em>mappilīʾ laʿăśôt</em>, doing wondrously) as the angel ascends in the flame — creates the theophanic sign parallel to Gideon's encounter (6:21). The rock-altar and fire-from-rock is the consistent sign of the divine warrior's presence in Judges. The grain offering (<em>minḥāh</em>) alongside the animal sacrifice reflects the full burnt offering procedure of Lev 1-2: both components were standard at formal sacrifices. The 'doing wonders' language connects this to the Exodus tradition of YHWH's 'wonders' (<em>niplāʾôt</em>) — the theophany at Zorah is presented as a miniature Sinai-event.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The angel ascending in the flame of the altar — 'it happened as the flame went up from the altar toward heaven that the angel of YHWH went up in the flame' — is the clearest statement in Judges of the angel's divine identity. Fire as the medium of divine ascent recalls the pillar of fire in the wilderness (Exod 13:21-22) and the theophany to Moses in the burning bush (Exod 3:2). The angel does not walk away; he ascends — vertically, in fire, toward heaven. Manoah and his wife 'fell on their faces to the ground' — the prostration response to divine encounter that runs from Abraham (Gen 17:3) through the Gospels (Matt 17:6) to Revelation (Rev 1:17).</p>",
    "21": "<p>'The angel of YHWH appeared no more to Manoah and to his wife' — the statement of finality marks the end of the theophanic series. The angel's mission was accomplished: the birth announcement was given, confirmed, and the offering received. The cessation of divine appearances after the mission's completion is consistent across Judges theophanies: the angel appears, delivers the commission, and departs. The verse then makes explicit what has been implicit: 'Then Manoah knew that he was the angel of YHWH' — the recognition arrives only after the departure, confirming the post-hoc pattern of theophanic recognition in Judges (cf. Gideon's recognition in 6:22).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Manoah's fear — 'We shall surely die, for we have seen God' — is the standard theophany-terror response, grounded in the ancient belief that full divine encounter was fatal (Exod 33:20). The word 'God' (<em>ʾĕlōhîm</em>) rather than 'angel of YHWH' in Manoah's statement shows his theological resolution: the one who ascended in the altar fire was not a messenger but God himself. Manoah has correctly identified the nature of the encounter. His wife's counterargument (v23) will work by a different logical register: not 'you are wrong about who it was' but 'if he intended to kill us, the evidence does not support that intention.'</p>",
    "23": "<p>The wife's theological argument is a model of practical reasoning from divine consistency: 'If YHWH had meant to kill us, he would not have accepted a burnt offering and grain offering at our hands, or shown us all these things, or now announced to us such things as these.' The argument has three elements: (1) YHWH accepted our sacrifice — divine acceptance of sacrifice implies relationship, not judgment; (2) YHWH showed us wonders — wonders are displays of divine grace, not harbingers of death; (3) YHWH gave us a birth announcement — a promise of future blessing is incompatible with a plan to immediately kill. This is covenantal reasoning: the pattern of YHWH's past actions in this encounter is inconsistent with a plan for their death. The wife reasons better than her husband.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The birth and naming of Samson — 'the woman bore a son and called his name Samson, and the young man grew, and YHWH blessed him' — is terse compared to the elaborate birth announcements. <em>Šimšôn</em> (Samson, H8123) is related to <em>šemeš</em> (sun, H8121) — possibly 'sunny one' or 'solar' — which has generated much scholarly discussion about possible solar mythology underlying the Samson traditions. Whether the name has cosmological freight or is simply a personal name derived from a common noun, the connection to the sun (which rises and sets, whose strength waxes and wanes) has been noted by interpreters from antiquity. YHWH's blessing marks the child as set apart from birth for divine purposes.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'The Spirit of YHWH began to stir him (<em>palʿam</em>) in Mahaneh-dan, between Zorah and Eshtaol' — the verb <em>pāʿam</em> (H6470, to thrust/disturb/stir — used of inner agitation or impulse) describes not the full rushing-upon empowerment of battle (which uses <em>ṣālaḥ</em>) but a preliminary stirring, a divine restlessness that begins to manifest in Samson. Mahaneh-dan ('camp of Dan,' also mentioned in 18:12 as a staging point for the Danite migration) was in the Shephelah between Samson's hometown Zorah and Eshtaol — the very border region of Philistine and Israelite territory. The Spirit's stirring begins in the most contested geographic space, preparing Samson for his boundary-crossing, rule-breaking, culture-challenging mission against the Philistines.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('context', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('context', 'judges', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'judges mkt-context: wrote {total} verses across ch 11-13')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
